  "text": "¼ 0:018 þ 0:143 ¼ 0:161; p = 0.02), which indicates a higher re-election probability for physically attractive female MPs (consistent with, for instance, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Perceived beauty displays a much weaker association with holding an important political office (b . No significant effects are observed for perceived competence on all three measures of political success. Taken together, these results suggest that (perceived) physical beauty appears to provide a benefit to (particularly female) politicians in the electoral arena, but that (perceived) likability is a more valuable asset once the elections are over. This configuration may well reflect the varying preferences of the different decision makers at both time points of the democratic process: that is, voters in elections and other politicians after the elections. (4) and (5) are estimated using a Poisson regression, whereas Column (6) is based on a logit model.",
